         <div type="commentary" subtype="frontmatter" xml:space="preserve"><p>Fragment of a medical catechism possibly from a manual of ophthalmology (for <emph rend="italics">erotapokrisis</emph> see <ref target="http://www.papirologia.unipr.it/CPGM/medicalia/vocab/index.php?tema=8">Medicalia Online s.v. Catechism</ref>). The left-hand side is missing. The preserved section dealing with <emph rend="italics">glaucoma</emph> (ll. 1-2) and <emph rend="italics">staphyloma</emph> (ll. 3-17) is partly paralleled by P.Ross.Georg. 1.20 (LDAB 4778; MP3 2343), P.Aberd. 11 (LDAB 4539; MP3 2342) and by medical authors (cf. <listBibl><bibl><ref target="http://papyri.info/biblio/52645">Marganne 1978</ref></bibl></listBibl>, 313-20; <listBibl><bibl><ref target="http://papyri.info/biblio/13669">Marganne 1994</ref></bibl></listBibl>, 97-132). On <emph rend="italics">staphyloma</emph> see now <ref target="http://www.papirologia.unipr.it/CPGM/medicalia/vocab/index.php?tema=21">Medicalia Online s.v.</ref> Questions and responses are articulated with blank spaces at right (ll. 3, 5-6, 14) and marked by poss. indented headings (ll. 3, 6, 11-2, 15). Papyrus scrap (11.6x4.5 cm) written on the verso in a sloping hand. On the recto traces of a document dating to III-IV AD.</p><p><note type="footnote" xml:lang="en">This papyrus has been digitally edited by Isabella Bonati as part of the Project "DIGMEDTEXT - Online Humanities Scholarship: A Digital Medical Library based on Ancient Texts" (ERC-AdG-2013, Grant Agreement no. 339828) funded by the European Research Council at the University of Parma (Principal Investigator: Prof. Isabella Andorlini). The digital edition is mostly based on the previous edition (C. Magdelaine, "Testi Medici su Papiro", ed. I. Andorlini, pp. 64-77).</note></p></div>
